   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Tancred
                           and Sigismunda</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>Tancred and Sigismunda</title>; A Tragedy, In Five
                              Acts; By <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">James Thomson</ref>.
                              As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>.
                        London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp.
                        3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A
                              Collection of Plays, Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. XIII. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Love for Love</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Mourning Bride</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><ref target="people.html#Muhammad"
                           >Mahomet</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Tancred and
                              Sigismunda</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Suspicious
                              Husband</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and
                        Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged
                        at the <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref>
                        on March 18<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1745. Laura DeWitt and Mary A.
                        Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                           Archive</hi>.</note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>This beautiful poem, in dialogue, called a drama, has but few attractions in
               representation, although it is the work of the celebrated author of "<title>The
                  Seasons</title>."<note><ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">James
                  Thomson</ref>'s nature and landscape poem <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                        Seasons</title></hi> (1730) was much revered by his contemporaries and
                  influenced Romantic period poetic depictions of nature.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> was born in 1700, in Roxburgh, a
               shire in Scotland, the son of the minister of the parish of Ednam.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> was born in Ednam, a small
                  village in Roxburghshire, a historic county in the Southern Uplands of Scotland.
                     <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>'s father was the
                  Presbyterian minister of Ednam at the time of <ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>'s birth.</note> He received his
               early education at Jedburgh, and was afterwards admitted to the university of
               Edinburgh. He was designed for the church, but the Muses presided over his
               inclination, and allured him from sacred study and his native land, to seek
               reputation, and other reward, in the capital of England.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> attended the Jedburgh Grammar
                  School in 1712, where he was an apparently unremarkable student. In 1715, <ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> entered the College of
                  Edinburgh with aspirations to enter the Presbyterian ministry. While in Edinburgh,
                     <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> joined the literary
                  Grotesque Club, where he met his lifelong friend <ref
                     target="people.html#MalletDavid">David Mallet</ref>. After getting a few of his
                  poems published in <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Edinburgh
                        Miscellany</title></hi>, <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames"
                     >Thomson</ref> followed <ref target="people.html#MalletDavid">Mallet</ref> to
                  London in 1725 in hopes of furthering his career as a poet.</note></p>

            <p>His first pursuit was attained as soon as he published his
               "<title>Winter</title>,"&#8212;which appeared before the other Seasons&#8212;but more
               solid renumeration came both slowly and precariously&#8212;for, like most poets, <ref
                  target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> was often in necessitous
                  circumstances.<note>"Winter," what would become the first poem in <ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>The Seasons</title></hi>, was first published in 1726.</note> Yet he
               was favoured with the friendship of <ref target="people.html#PopeAlexander"
                  >Pope</ref>, and protected by the <ref target="people.html#TalbotCharlesBaron"
                  >Lord Chancellor Talbot</ref>, with whose son he made the <fw type="sig"><hi
                     rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>tour of Europe:&#8212;but, by the
               death of that son, soon after his return, and the decease of the <ref
                  target="people.html#TalbotCharlesBaron">Chancellor</ref> immediately succeeding,
               the poet was reduced from a degree of affluence to poverty; as he merely held a
               lucrative place under his patron, which fell with him.<note>In 1730, <ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> became the tutor and travelling
                  companion of <ref target="people.html#TalbotCharlesBaron">Charles Talbot</ref>'s
                  eldest son for the duration of his tour of the Continent. The young Talbot died in
                  1733, at which point the elder <ref target="people.html#TalbotCharlesBaron"
                     >Talbot</ref>, newly made Lord High Chancellor, provided <ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> with the sinecure position of
                  secretary of briefs. <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> lost the
                  post in 1737 upon <ref target="people.html#TalbotCharlesBaron">Lord Talbot</ref>'s
                  death.</note></p>

            <p>The present tragedy was first acted in 1744.&#8212;<ref
                  target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> was the original Tancred, and <ref
                  target="people.html#CibberSusannah">Mrs. Cibber</ref> the renowned
               Sigismunda.&#8212;The story is taken from "<title>Gil Blas</title>," and, as the
               author added little more than poetry to the fable, it is devoid of all that incident
               by which every act should be diversified, to established the just title of a dramatic
                  work.<note>This play was first acted on March 18<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>,
                  1745. <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">David Garrick</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#CibberSusannah">Susannah Cibber</ref> debuted the roles of
                  the eponymous young lovers. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Gil Blas</title></hi>
                  (in French, <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Histoire de Gil Blas de
                        Santillane</title></hi>) is a 1715 picaresque novel by <ref
                     target="people.html#LeSageAlain">Alain-René Lesage</ref>. It appears that <ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> is mistaken, however, as
                  scholars believe this play to be inspired by "<title>The Tale of Ghismonda and
                     Guiscardo</title>" from the first novella of Day Four of <ref
                     target="people.html#Boccaccio">Giovanni Boccaccio</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Decameron</title></hi> (c.
               1348-1353).</note></p>

            <p>The soft flowing love of Tancred and Sigismunda may find admirers by the fireside, on
               a long winter's evening; but can with difficulty obtain listeners in a brilliant
               theatre, where a thousand objects divert the attention which is not seized at once by
               some bold occurrence on the stage, and fastened to the subject of its concern by
               perpetual variety.</p>

            <p>The interest, which the town has taken of late in seeing a child represent a man, has
               recalled this tragedy from the library once more to the theatre. But this is no proof
               against the dulness of the production. The taste, which is irregular, will combine
               irregularities; and why should not exquisite verses be taken for a play, whilst an
               exquisite little boy is received as an actor?<note>Child actors, particularly males,
                  became an integral part of the early nineteenth-century English stage,
                  reinvigorating public interest in theatre. The production of <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Tancred and Sigismunda</title></hi> that <ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> attended, likely in 1803 or
                  1804, featured <ref target="people.html#BettyWilliam">Master Betty</ref> as
                  Tancred, at which point he would have been 12 or 13.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#SiddonsHarriet">Mrs. H. Siddons</ref> wants nothing to make
               the part of Sigismunda impressive, but a Tancred of her own height.</p>
            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>The author of this work died in the forty-ninth year of his age, of a fever caught by
               imprudently taking a boat from Hammersmith to Kew, when he was previously heated by a
               hasty walk from London.<note><ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>
                  died of a fever on August 27<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1748, at the age of 47.
                     <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> draws the notion of <ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>'s death resulting from a boat
                  ride from <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Samuel Johnson</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Lives of the Most Eminent English Poets; with
                        Critical Observations on their Works</title></hi> (1781, vol. IV, pp.
                  264-265).</note> He died at his house in Richmond, a pensioner of <ref
                  target="people.html#FrederickPrinceofWales">Frederick, Prince of Wales</ref>, our
               present <ref target="people.html#GeorgeIIIKingofGreatBritain">King</ref>'s father;
               and has a monument to his memory in Westminster Abbey.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> died at his home in Richmond
                  upon Thames, a town in south-west London. <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames"
                     >Thomson</ref> has a memorial beside <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakespeare</ref>'s in the
                  Poet's Corner of the famous Westminster Abbey graveyard in London. <ref
                     target="people.html#FrederickPrinceofWales">Prince Frederick</ref> had granted
                     <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> a pension of £100 per year
                  starting in 1740, when <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>
                  collaborated with <ref target="people.html#MalletDavid">Mallet</ref> on the masque
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Alfred</title></hi> to be performed at a gala
                  for <ref target="people.html#FrederickPrinceofWales">Frederick</ref>'s daughter's
                  birthday.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> appears, from all accounts
               received of him, to have been a man of mild and modest manners, and of depressed
               spirits. <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Dr. Johnson</ref> says, he was fat,
               and accuses him of indolence&#8212;here is another irregularity&#8212;for <ref
                  target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> was born on the other side of the
                  Tweed.<note>In his <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Lives of the Most Eminent
                        English Poets; with Critical Observations on their Works</title></hi>, <ref
                     target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref> writes of <ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>: "<ref
                     target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref> was of stature above the middle
                  size, and <hi rendition="#italics">more fat than bard beseems</hi>, of a dull
                  countenance, and a gross, unanimated, uninviting appearance" (1781, vol. IV, p.
                  265). <ref target="people.html#ThomsonJames">Thomson</ref>'s birthplace of Ednam,
                  Scotland, is a few miles north of the River Tweed, which marks the
                  Scottish-English border, a region that was known for its poor inhabitants who eked
                  out meagre livings.</note></p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw>
         </div>
